I drive 83 mile ( 133 km ) each way. 166 miles / 266 km km everyday to commute to a Rural city Hospital for my work. 40,000 miles / 64,000 km or more a year.

My requirement are few.

  1. Good tire that track well with good sidewall so it does not sway. Do not hydroplane and get good traction on snowy road.
  2. Good headlight that illuminate evenly.
  3. Tight suspension but not harsh. You do not want a sport car or limousine suspension. feeling every bump on the road or float like a boat for a long drive day in day out is not fun.
  4. A very reliable car. getting stranded while on long commute is not fun.

Originally Answered: Which cars are the best for long commutes?

In order of importance. Choose the car with the most comfortable seat. Try out a few. Youll be sitting in it for a long time. Then choose the entertainment system. You wont want to be bored. Then choose one that connects to your phone so you can tell someone not to worry when you are stuck in the snow. Then choose a quiet car with low emissions. Then think about a speed limiter so you wont worry about breaking limits. Cruise control can be useful too.

Dont worry about the colour. On a long commute your car will always be dirty.

The car is very comfortable and has a nice sound system.

For a long commute I would ensure the vehicle has additional safety features including lane departure warning and automatic emergency brakes. Drowsy driving is the same risk as drinking and driving.

I believe most cars now have Bluetooth stereo standard. Turn on a podcast and you will not have to be concerned over the radio dead zones.

Of course, you want to be sure your vehicle choice has excellent fuel economy and a low cost of ownership (maintenance) to reduce impact on the environment and your wallet
